ng**: The code increments `leaderChanges` counter on transitions, sets `hasLeader` and `isLeader` metrics\n\n### Key Differences\n\n| Aspect | Kubernetes | etcd |\n|--------|-----------|------|\n| **Mechanism** | Lease-based (optimistic locking) | Raft consensus (voting-based) |\n| **Failover Detection** | Lease expiration after LeaseDuration | Heartbeat timeout (TickMs) |\n| **Re-election Trigger** | Manual acquisition when lease expired | Automatic via Raft election |\n| **Coordination** | API server (Lease resources) | In-cluster consensus |\n| **Consistency Guarantee** | Best-effort (tolerates clock skew) | Strong (Raft guarantees) |\n| **Fencing** | Not guaranteed (can have multiple leaders briefly) | Guaranteed single leader (Raft) |\n\nBoth approaches provide leader election suitable for their architectures: Kubernetes leverages its API for distributed coordination, while etcd embeds consensus as its core mechanism."
